Here’s a sketch of the row–reduction on the augmented matrix

\[
\begin{pmatrix}
-1 & -3 & 2 &\vrule& 14\\
-1 & 2 & -3 &\vrule& -4\\
3 & 1 & -2 &\vrule& 6
\end{pmatrix}
\]

1. Multiply the first row by –1 to make a leading 1, and then use it to eliminate \(x\) in rows 2 and 3:

\[
\begin{pmatrix}
1 & 3 & -2 &\vrule& -14\\
-1 & 2 & -3 &\vrule& -4\\
3 & 1 & -2 &\vrule& 6
\end{pmatrix}
\;\xrightarrow{\substack{R_2\to R_2+R_1\\R_3\to R_3-3R_1}}\;
\begin{pmatrix}
1 & 3 & -2 &\vrule& -14\\
0 & 5 & -5 &\vrule& -18\\
0 & -8 & 4 &\vrule& 48
\end{pmatrix}
\]

2. Divide the new row 2 by 5 and use it to kill the \(y\)–entry in row 3:

\[
\begin{pmatrix}
1 & 3 & -2 &\vrule& -14\\
0 & 1 & -1 &\vrule& -\tfrac{18}{5}\\
0 & -8 & 4 &\vrule& 48
\end{pmatrix}
\;\xrightarrow{R_3\to R_3+8R_2}\;
\begin{pmatrix}
1 & 3 & -2 &\vrule& -14\\
0 & 1 & -1 &\vrule& -\tfrac{18}{5}\\
0 & 0 & -4 &\vrule& \tfrac{96}{5}
\end{pmatrix}
\]

3. Finally, divide row 3 by \(-4\) and back-substitute:

\[
\begin{pmatrix}
1 & 3 & -2 &\vrule& -14\\
0 & 1 & -1 &\vrule& -\tfrac{18}{5}\\
0 & 0 & 1 &\vrule& -\tfrac{24}{5}
\end{pmatrix}
\quad\Longrightarrow\quad
\begin{cases}
z=-\tfrac{24}{5},\\
y - z=-\tfrac{18}{5}\;\Rightarrow\;y=-\tfrac{42}{5},\\
x +3y-2z=-14\;\Rightarrow\;x=\tfrac{8}{5}.
\end{cases}
\]

Answer:
\[
(x,y,z)=\bigl(\tfrac{8}{5},\,-\tfrac{42}{5},\,-\tfrac{24}{5}\bigr).
\]
